{"add":{"doc":{"id":"fbf542b2def35ab738c4a72bf4b5243a1c46a0a94f8f0c87caf8a7566a62400d","url":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/81/Forbes_building_in_NYC.jpg/100px-Forbes_building_in_NYC.jpg","previous":[],"after":["B. C. Forbes, a financial columnist for the Hearst papers, and his partner Walter Drey, the general manager of the Magazine of Wall Street,[4] founded Forbes magazine in 1917.[5][6] Forbes provided the money and the name and Drey provided the publishing expertise. The original name of the magazine was Forbes: Devoted to Doers and Doings.[4] Drey became vice-president of the B.C. Forbes Publishing Company,[7] while B.C. Forbes became editor-in-chief, a post he held until his death in 1954. B.C. Forbes was assisted in his later years by his two eldest sons, Bruce Charles Forbes (1916–1964) and Malcolm Stevenson Forbes (1917–1990)."]}}}